Welcome to FiveThirtyEight‚Äôs weekly politics chat. The transcript below has been lightly edited.
sarahf (Sarah Frostenson, politics editor): Welcome, everyone, to a special debate-focused preview edition of our weekly politics chat!! In recent weeks, we‚Äôve talked a lot about the different strategies the candidates should use on the debate stage, who the lineup is good for (and who it‚Äôs bad for) and whether the field might be consolidating around a handful of candidates.
So today, let‚Äôs have a little fun with the question of candidate debate strategy and play a game of buy/sell/hold with PredictIt prop bets (plus some I made up). We checked the prices (given in cents) of a bunch of propositions at noon Eastern on Tuesday and then translated those prices into probabilities. (We know that‚Äôs not exactly right, but it‚Äôs close enough.)
And in case you forgot how to play buy/sell/hold:
OK, let‚Äôs start with a üå∂ spicy üå∂ proposition. Buy, sell or hold: Elizabeth Warren will win the 2020 presidential Democratic nomination? (33 percent)
