And the most damning stat of his candidacy was his popularity at home ‚Äî New Yorkers don‚Äôt like him and didn‚Äôt want him to run!
It‚Äôs like if those at home, who in theory know you best, don‚Äôt like you all that much, why try to catapult yourself onto a national stage? Former New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani was at least popular when he mounted his 2008 presidential bid.
nrakich: Oh, see, Sarah, that‚Äôs kind of why I don‚Äôt think he‚Äôll drop out anytime soon.
De Blasio strikes me as the kind of candidate who isn‚Äôt really running to win, just to throw some rhetorical bombs and maybe have a good time.
So why let having almost no chance of winning the nomination stop you?
Reportedly, de Blasio doesn‚Äôt like his day job as New York City mayor. So I think he‚Äôll try to prolong his presidential campaign as long as possible ‚Äî to stay away from City Hall.
geoffrey.skelley: Resources could be a problem though ‚Äî de Blasio raised only $1.1 million by the end of June and had just 6,700 donors. Yeesh. So yeah, I can see him leaving just because he can‚Äôt afford to stay in.
sarahf: Yeesh is right. OK, Geoffrey. Last round! Make it count.
geoffrey.skelley: All right, I think there‚Äôs an easy pick that I would take if we had four rounds, but given we only have three picks, I think I‚Äôm going to go for my sleeper choice: former Texas Rep. Beto O‚ÄôRourke. I think it‚Äôs possible that he might actually consider running for Senate again. He‚Äôs polling at 2 percent nationally with no obvious path for improvement, and he‚Äôs even worse off in Iowa and New Hampshire.
