sarahf: So as Amelia mentioned earlier, what sets this shooting apart from some other (although not all) mass shootings is its link to white extremist ideology. And so I wonder what impact that will have on public opinion moving forward, including how Americans think about aspects of Trump‚Äôs rhetoric.
ameliatd: It‚Äôs really hard to draw a direct line between a politician‚Äôs rhetoric and a particular act of violence. But I‚Äôm working on a story looking at the research on this topic, and pretty much all of the social scientists I‚Äôve spoken with agree that hostile political rhetoric, particularly from someone as influential as a president, can embolden people who already had prejudiced views or were prone to violence.
perry: This is really a conversation about Trump, right?
The general public is against white supremacist language and against mass shootings. So the core question is whether Trump will stop invoking the ideas expressed by the shooter in El Paso, and whether he can reframe his rhetoric and approach to make it clear he is against increased immigration, and not Latinos and nonwhite people in the U.S.
natesilver: Yeah, it‚Äôs a conversation about Trump. I feel like people are beating around the bush too much. It‚Äôs a conversation about Trump.
sarahf: That‚Äôs fair, but it‚Äôs more than Trump, too. It‚Äôs also some of the commentary on Fox News and in right-wing conspiracy theories. Granted, Trump has had a role in bringing these ideas into the mainstream, but I‚Äôd say the problem is bigger than him, too.
perry: But we had a person kill a lot of people while invoking language that the president and his team have regularly used. I don‚Äôt think that most Americans view the country as facing an ‚Äúinvasion‚Äù of immigrants. Or that most Americans approve of Trump‚Äôs language. Other Republicans, like Mitch McConnell, are not talking about immigrant invasions all the time.
So my big questions are: ‚ÄúWill Trump stop invoking these ideas?‚Äù and ‚ÄúWill the Republican Party push him to stop?‚Äù I think the answer to both these questions is maybe.
Do others agree?
sarahf: I don‚Äôt know. Right now there seems to be more of a distancing from the language Trump and his team has used more than a rebuke. Trump‚Äôs acting White House chief of staff, for instance, told ABC News that he doesn‚Äôt think it‚Äôs fair to blame Trump and that the problem predates his administration.
ameliatd: Right, the answer so far seems to be that these shootings haven‚Äôt yet convinced Trump‚Äôs allies to start condemning his language.
natesilver: Not to be too both-sides-y, but let‚Äôs not forget the 2017 Congressional baseball shooting in this discussion where a gunman targeted Republican legislators. So, yes, maybe we have a rising tide of political violence overall, of which Trump‚Äôs rhetoric plays an important part, but it‚Äôs not necessarily the only cause.
perry: But if the White House is emphasizing that it‚Äôs opposed to white supremacy Trump may have to stop saying things white nationalists say.
Trump‚Äôs re-election campaign has already put out more than 2,000 Facebook ads that include the word ‚Äúinvasion‚Äù this year as part of his message on immigration at the U.S.-Mexico border, according to an analysis by The New York Times. So did Saturday end that? I think the answer might be yes. I‚Äôm not sure, but that could be at least one potential shift.
natesilver: Do we really expect Trump to back down though? He seems to be convinced that this stuff is central to his re-election efforts. And he‚Äôs not the sort of guy who stops doing something just because people tell him to stop doing it.
ameliatd: I also think the fact that he‚Äôs being attacked as racist by many of the Democratic candidates could make him dig in even further.
nrakich: The White House also condemned white supremacy after Charlottesville, but of course, Trump later returned to his inflammatory rhetoric.
perry: I think this shooting is different than Charlottesville, though. Or anything else that has happened. People were literally killed by someone who invoked the same language as the president.
I don‚Äôt want to suggest something is a game-changer, but I think this is potentially an important moment. Because even if, say, Trump does not change, maybe the Republican Party shifts in some way?
nrakich: A woman died in Charlottesville, too.
I am just skeptical of any claims that ‚Äúthis time it‚Äôs different.‚Äù
The ‚Äúinvasion‚Äù language may disappear in the short term because it will be seen as too inflammatory for the next couple months. But I don‚Äôt think there will be any kind of permanent shift.
perry: That‚Äôs a reasonable position, and probably the right one.
But if Trump stops describing what‚Äôs happening at the southern border as an ‚Äúinvasion,‚Äù that would be significant. Words, in my view, do matter.
And that ‚Äúinvasion‚Äù framing is really racist.
What I‚Äôm really trying to isolate here is that a person killed people using the same words the president has used to stoke fears about immigrants in the U.S.
Does that make what happened in El Paso different than what happened in Charlottesville? ‚ÄúNo‚Äù is probably the right answer. But I‚Äôm not sure.
nrakich: Also, this isn‚Äôt the first time during the Trump administration that a gun was used to murder multiple people as part of a hate crime ‚Äî the Pittsburgh synagogue shooting targeted Jews, for example.
ameliatd: I do think the lack of condemnation from Republicans is significant. When the response is distancing, not censure, that sends a signal to Trump. But I do think you‚Äôre right, Perry, that this is an important moment for Trump and the GOP.
sarahf: The gunman also allegedly wrote that his views ‚Äúpredate Trump,‚Äù perhaps in anticipation of the blowback. And given that more Republicans haven‚Äôt spoken out, I‚Äôm not sure how this will change the conversation around gun violence or the fact that Trump‚Äôs rhetoric can inspire violence, other than maybe Republicans and Democrats further retreat into their partisan camps.
perry: I don‚Äôt think that Americans‚Äô views on gun will change much, in part because most Americans, even a significant bloc of Republicans, already favor a lot of gun control measures. Americans overall are also supportive of immigration and on average are growing less prejudiced since Trump‚Äôs election (not more), so I think incidents like the El Paso shooting are likely to further those those trends ‚Äî not reverse them.
And so I think we‚Äôre likely to see more polls showing that certain kinds of racial rhetoric should be out of bounds. For instance, Trump telling female congresswomen of color to ‚Äúgo back‚Äù to their countries was very unpopular (although a majority of Republicans said that the attacks were acceptable).
natesilver: The gun control discussion is also REALLY complicated by the fact that Wyoming has as many senators as California. The Senate has big, built-in bias toward rural states, and few issues have a stronger urban-rural divide than guns do.
ameliatd: It‚Äôs at least possible that we‚Äôll see some more movement on something like red-flag laws, though, right? These are laws that would help temporarily take guns away from people who are at a high risk of violence, and that have passed in a significant number of states since the Parkland shooting last year. And they seem to be getting some support from Republicans in Congress.
nrakich: The (Republican) governor of Ohio proposed one on Tuesday.
ameliatd: And that‚Äôs a policy that the NRA has supported in the abstract ‚Äî although they‚Äôve also worked to water them down when they‚Äôve actually been introduced.
