perry: So on the Democratic side, this is interesting. Many of the debates and the broader discussion of the primary are framed around, ‚ÄúDo you prioritize bold change or winning the election?‚Äù And that framing helps Biden. I‚Äôm not sure what the Medicare for All equivalent (bold policy that can be painted as electorally risky) is for Iran. The issue just doesn‚Äôt have the same dynamics. So this could be an issue where the non-Biden candidates can make arguments without being trapped in a dilemma over how their stances poll.
Sanders has really leaned into this issue by connecting it to his broader opposition to the Iraq War, as well as his view that the U.S. should be less eager to intervene abroad. Biden, by contrast, has struggled to reconcile his vote in support of the Iraq War. A voter in Iowa asked him about it on Saturday ‚Äî and he said he opposed the war from the beginning, which is not accurate.
clare.malone: Yeah, that was a weird moment.
perry: So because the foreign policy lines are less clear, I think it‚Äôs an opportunity for the non-Biden candidates to challenge him in a fresh way. And it‚Äôs harder to imagine that Biden‚Äôs Iraq vote won‚Äôt come up in next week‚Äôs debate.
clare.malone: I think that there is definitely potential upside for Sanders: He can point out that he‚Äôs principled and anti-war, which the progressive base will like, but he has also pointed out that his policy stance of getting out of the Middle East is exactly what Trump promised. So, in some ways, he‚Äôs trying to showcase what he thinks is his general election advantage: a different kind of (populist or outsider) appeal to Trump voters.
nrakich: Yeah, I wonder how big of a role Biden‚Äôs Iraq vote will play. I feel like other candidates are seizing on it out of necessity ‚Äî since otherwise, foreign policy is an issue where voters give Biden a big advantage:
